{{geometry-stub}}

In mathematics, the '''annulus theorem''' (formerly called the '''annulus conjecture''') states roughly that the region between two well-behaved spheres is an [[Annulus (mathematics)|annulus]]. It is closely related to the '''stable homeomorphism conjecture''' (now proved) which states that every orientation-preserving homeomorphism of Euclidean space is stable.

==Statement==
If ''S'' and ''T'' are topological spheres in Euclidean space, with ''S'' contained in ''T'', then it is not true in general that the region between them is an [[Annulus (mathematics)|annulus]],  because of the existence of [[wild sphere]]s in dimension at least 3. So the annulus theorem has to be stated to exclude these examples, by adding some condition to ensure that ''S'' and ''T'' are well behaved. There are several ways to do this.

The annulus theorem states that if any homeomorphism ''h'' of '''R'''<sup>''n''</sup> to itself maps the unit ball ''B'' into its interior, then ''B'' &minus; ''h''(interior(''B'')) is homeomorphic to the annulus '''S'''<sup>''n''&minus;1</sup>&times;[0,1].

==History of proof==
The annulus theorem is trivial in dimensions 0 and 1. It was proved in dimension 2 by {{harvtxt|Radó|1924}}, in dimension 3 by {{harvtxt|Moise|1952}}, in dimension 4 by {{harvtxt|Quinn|1982}}, and in dimensions at least 5 by {{harvtxt|Kirby|1969}}.

==The stable homeomorphism conjecture==

A homeomorphism of '''R'''<sup>''n''</sup> is called '''stable''' if it is a product of homeomorphisms each of which is the identity on some non-empty open set. 
The '''stable homeomorphism conjecture''' states that every orientation-preserving homeomorphism of '''R'''<sup>''n''</sup> is stable. {{harvtxt|Brown|Gluck|1964}} previously showed that the  stable homeomorphism conjecture is equivalent to the annulus conjecture, so it is true.

