'''Elayne Arrington''' is an American [[mathematician]] and [[engineer]]. She was the first [[African Americans|African American]] woman to graduate from the [[University of Pittsburgh]]'s School of Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2017/02/15/pioneer-role-model-for-next-generation.html|title=Pioneer role model for next generation|last=Wojcik|first=Joe|date=15 February 2017|website=www.bizjournals.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref> In 2017 Arrington received the Distinguished Alumnus Award from the African American Alumni Council.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://swsg.org/four-inspiring-african-american-women-honored-at-university-of-pittsburgh/|title=Four Inspiring African-American Women Honored at University of Pittsburgh - SWSG|date=2017-07-20|work=SWSG|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en-US}}</ref>
== Early life and education == Elayne Arrington grew up in [[West Mifflin, Pennsylvania|West Mifflin]], [[Pennsylvania]], and graduated from Homestead High School in 1957 where she was [[valedictorian]], receiving the country's second highest mathematics [[SAT]] score (797 out of 800).<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pts.edu/Elayne_Arrington|title=Elayne Arrington|website=www.pts.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-05-30}}</ref> She received was recommended for a scholarship to study [[mechanical engineering]] at the University of Pittsburgh, but the sponsor, the Mesta Machine Company withdrew her application for the scholarship saying that the money had to be given to a man because women do not finish engineering programs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/opinion/Op-Ed/2017/02/09/Robert-Hill-Pittsburgh-s-own-Hidden-Figures/stories/201702280022|title=Robert Hill: Pittsburgh’s own ‘Hidden Figures’|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2018-05-30|language=en}}</ref> In 1961 she became the first woman to graduate from the University of Pittsburgh's School of Engineering. She earned a [[Master's degree|master's]] in mathematics from the [[University of Dayton]], Ohio. While working on her master's Arrington also took math courses at Oxford University.<ref name=":1" /> She became the 17th African-American woman in the United States to earn a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in mathematics.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />
== Career == Arrington became an [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace engineer]] at the [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base]]'s Foreign Technology Division in [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]], [[Ohio]],<ref name=":0" /> where she worked on performance analysis of [[Soviet Union]] aircraft. Later she returned to the University of Pittsburgh where she became an associate professor of mathematics.<ref name=":1" />
